## 5. Critical Functions & Recovery Priorities
Functions are recovered in priority order. Tier 1 (highest priority) functions are those whose loss causes immediate patient, regulatory, or severe financial harm — typically PHI availability and the production application. Tier 2 and Tier 3 functions are recovered as resources permit. Record the prioritized sequence in the BIA register and align it with the DR runbooks.

## 6. Continuity Strategies
For each critical function, define how continuity is achieved:
- **Technology resilience:** [AWS] multi-AZ deployment, automated failover, and cross-region recovery per `disaster-recovery-plan.md.template`.
- **Workforce continuity:** Remote-work capability, cross-training, and documented succession for key roles so no single person is a single point of failure.
- **Facilities:** [Alternate work locations / fully remote posture]; loss of a physical office does not halt operations.
- **Third-party dependencies:** Identify critical vendors, their SLAs, and fallback options; manage vendor resilience per `../vendor/third-party-risk-management-policy.md.template`.
- **Data:** Backups and restoration are governed by `[backup-policy]` and validated through DR testing.
- **Manual workarounds:** [Documented interim procedures] for the highest-priority functions when systems are unavailable.

## 7. Crisis Management & Communications
1. The [Crisis Management Team] is activated by the [Security Officer / COO] when a disruption exceeds [threshold].
2. A maintained **call tree / contact list** and **out-of-band communications channel** (independent of primary email/Slack) ensure the team can coordinate even if primary systems are down.
3. Internal, customer, and regulatory communications are coordinated by the [Communications Lead] with [Legal]. PHI-breach notifications follow `../healthcare/hipaa-breach-notification-procedure.md.template`.

## 8. Roles & Responsibilities
| Role | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| [CEO] | Approves the plan; ultimate decision authority during a crisis. |
| [Security Officer / COO] | Owns this plan; activates the Crisis Management Team; coordinates recovery. |
| [CTO] | Directs technical recovery per the DR Plan. |
| [Privacy Officer] | Ensures PHI safeguards persist during emergency operation; manages breach obligations. |
| Function Owners | Maintain BIA entries and continuity procedures for their functions; lead their own recovery. |
| [Communications Lead] | Manages crisis communications. |
| All Workforce | Follow continuity instructions; maintain readiness; complete BCP awareness. |

See `../governance/roles-and-responsibilities.md.template` for full role definitions.

## 9. Testing & Maintenance
This plan is **tested at least annually** through [tabletop exercise / functional test / simulation], including at least one scenario exercising the DR Plan. Test scope, participants, findings, and corrective actions are documented and tracked to closure. The plan and BIA are reviewed at least annually and after any significant organizational, regulatory, or infrastructure change.

## 10. Exceptions
Exceptions to this plan require documented risk acceptance per `../governance/exceptions-and-waivers.md.template`, approved by the [Security Officer], time-bound, and recorded in the exceptions log.

## 11. Compliance, Monitoring & Enforcement
Compliance is verified through BIA currency, test completion, RTO/RPO achievement during tests, and corrective-action closure, reported to management review (`../governance/management-review.md.template`). Violations are handled per `../people/hr-security-policy.md.template`.

